Username Enumeration via Subtly Different Responses

This lab from the PortSwigger Web Security Academy demonstrates how small differences in authentication error
messages can lead to username enumeration and eventually allow an attacker to brute-force a user’s password. 
The application’s login functionality returns slightly different responses depending on whether the username 
exists or not. Although the error message appears almost identical to a human user, subtle differences such
as an extra space or punctuation can reveal whether a username is valid.

To begin the attack, a login request is captured using Burp Suite. An invalid username and password are submitted
to observe the structure of the POST /login request. The username parameter is then sent to the Intruder tool for

automated testing. Using the candidate username wordlist, multiple login requests are sent to the server with 
different usernames while keeping the password constant. During the attack, the Grep-Extract feature is used to
extract the error message returned in the response. Once the attack finishes, the responses are analyzed to
identify any small variation in the error message. One of the responses contains a slightly different message—for example,
a trailing space instead of a period—which indicates that the supplied username exists in the system.

After identifying a valid username, the attacker proceeds to the second stage: password brute-forcing. The discovered 
username is fixed in the request, and the payload position is moved to the password parameter. A password wordlist is
then used to send multiple login attempts automatically. While reviewing the results, a successful login attempt can
be identified by a different HTTP response, typically a 302 redirect, which indicates that authentication succeeded.
The corresponding password is then used together with the valid username to log into the application and access the
user’s account page, successfully completing the lab.

This vulnerability highlights a common security mistake where applications provide inconsistent authentication responses.
Even minor differences in response text, status codes, response length, or timing can allow attackers to systematically
discover valid usernames and perform targeted password attacks. To prevent this issue, developers should ensure that login
systems always return identical responses and response times for both valid and invalid usernames, thereby eliminating any
information leakage during the authentication process.
